OLS Refresher

In the classical regression model, we have the following assumptions:

  • (A.1) Linearity: \(\mathbf{Y}= \mathbf{X}\mathbb{\beta} + \epsilon\)
  • (A.2) Strict Exogeneity: \(\mathbb{E}[\epsilon | \mathbf{X}] = 0\). The explanatory variables are exogenous (uncorrelated with the error term). It implies:
    • (A.2.a) Weak Exogeneity: \(\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{X}_i\epsilon_i] = 0\). The explanatory variable is orthogonal to the error term.
    • (A.2.b) Unconditional Mean: \(\mathbb{E}[\epsilon_i] = 0\). The error term has zero mean.
  • (A.3) Full Rank: \(\text{rank}(\mathbf{X})=k\) (we need \(\mathbf{X}'\mathbf{X}\) to be invertible). A violation is perfect multicollinearity when some explanatory variables are linearly dependent.
  • (A.4) Spherical Errors: \(\mathbb{V}[\epsilon | \mathbf{X}] = \mathbb{E}[\epsilon\epsilon'|\mathbf{X}] = \sigma^2 I_n\). It implies:
    • (A.4.a) Homoskedasticity: \(\mathbb{V}[\epsilon_i | \mathbf{X}] = \sigma^2\). Error terms have constant variance. No heteroskedasticity.
    • (A.4.b) No Autocorrelation of Errors: \(\mathbb{Cov}[\epsilon_i, \epsilon_j | \mathbf{X}] = \mathbb{E}[\epsilon_i \epsilon_j | \mathbf{X}] = 0\) for \(i \neq j\). No serial correlation.
  • (A.5) Normality: \(\epsilon | \mathbf{X}\sim N(0, \sigma^2I_n)\). The error terms are normally distributed.

Under these assumptions, we can estimate the OLS estimator \(\hat{\beta} = (\mathbf{X}'\mathbf{X})^{-1}\mathbf{X}'Y\). Here are the properties of OLS Estimator:

  • Unbiasedness: \(\mathbb{E}[\hat{\beta} | \mathbf{X}] = \beta\).
  • Efficiency: The GaussMarkov theorem states that the OLS estimator is BLUE (Best Linear Unbiased Estimator).
  • Consistency: \(\hat{\beta} \xrightarrow{p} \beta\) as \(n \rightarrow \infty\).
  • Asymptotically Normality: \(\hat{\beta} \sim N(\beta, \sigma^2 (\mathbf{X}'\mathbf{X})^{-1})\).

Mathematics Refresher

This class assumes familiarity in probability theory and linear algebra. Check Harvards Math Prefresher if you need a refresher. Below I provide a quick review.

  • Prior Distribution: the probability of the parameter \(\theta\) before observing data, denoted as \(\xi(\theta)\).
  • Posterior Distribution: the conditional distribution of \(\theta\) given observed data \(X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_n\), denoted as \(\xi(\theta | x_1, \ldots, x_n)\).
  • Likelihood Function: \(\xi(\theta | x_1, \ldots, x_n) \propto f_n(x_1, \ldots, x_n | \theta) \xi(\theta)\). Here the likelihood function is \(L(\theta) = f_n(x_1, \ldots, x_n | \theta)\).
  • Again: \(\text{Posterior} \propto \text{Likelihood} \cdot \text{Prior}\)
  • Conjugate Families: choosing a conjugate prior that the posterior is in same family as the prior. We discuss three conjugate families: Normal-Normal, Beta-Binomial, and Gamma-Poisson.

Simulation

Here is a quick review for Monte Carlo Simulation in R.

# common distributions (prefix r-; for density, prefix d-; for cumulative, prefix p-)
rnorm() # Normal
runif() # Uniform
rbinom() # Binomial
rpois() # Poisson
rexp() # Exponential

# apply family functions
apply() 
sapply()
lapply()
tapply()
library(tidyverse)

# random seeds for reproducibility
set.seed(2025)

# sample() function
sample(x = 1:10, size = 6, replace = FALSE)
## [1] 4 1 7 6 3 2
sample(x = 1:10, size = 6, replace = TRUE)
## [1] 1 4 7 5 7 5
# replicate() function
replicate(3, rnorm(2))
##           [,1]       [,2]       [,3]
## [1,] 0.5689852 -0.8446397 -1.0643315
## [2,] 1.3944046 -0.6445391  0.1145143
# map family functions (from purrr)
modtwo <- function(.x) {
  return(.x %% 2)
}

map(c(1, 8, 13, 20), modtwo) # apply modtwo() to each element in the vector
## [[1]]
## [1] 1
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] 0
## 
## [[3]]
## [1] 1
## 
## [[4]]
## [1] 0
map_df(c(1, 8, 13, 20), function(.x) {
  return(data.frame(number = .x, 
                    mod2 = modtwo(.x)))
}) # apply modtwo() to each element in the vector and return a data frame
##   number mod2
## 1      1    1
## 2      8    0
## 3     13    1
## 4     20    0
# simulate a simple dataset using function()
simulate_lm <- function(n = 100, beta0 = 2, beta1 = 3) {
  x <- rnorm(n)
  y <- beta0 + beta1 * x + rnorm(n)
  return(data.frame(x = x, y = y))
}

data <- simulate_lm(100, 2, 3)

ggplot(data, aes(x = x, y = y)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
